        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "96e130550b9c7d4b",
        "text": "Leaving with preparation and farewell\nThe first station, namely the starting point of the fetching, is here. It is the place where I am-, and it is the place where I leave. Accordingly, my activities are divided into stationary and ambulatory. Still lingering here, I prepare myself, but also others and others, for the fact that I am about to fetch something here; and then I set out, go off to really do it. Therefore, the present chapter is divided into two large sections: the first deals with the preparations for leaving; the second then describes how the difficulties of leaving are solved by leaving with farewell.\nThe preparations, which are practically the first to be done and analytically the first to be unfolded, begin in the mind, and they continue and find their conclusion in reality: namely, with the fact that I prepare myself for my departure and that I make arrangements both for the period of my absence and for the time of my return.\nMental anticipation\nMore often than we are willing to admit, we get into an action, we lapse into a behavior, before we then set out to conceive it as an intentional action and to continue it. We invent the goal only when we are already on the way; but then we act as if we had pursued it from the beginning. Mostly our action, like our collecting and our life, has the form of the subsequent beginning.\nThat we cling to the idea that we first plan and then act, first envisage the goal and then set off: this clinging lives from the assumption that our actions have the form of a path. To walk a path is the pattern for what it means to perform an action."
      },
