      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "22956061c5fa567d",
        "text": "The fetching, however, is such a course. No wonder, then, that it fits so well into the scheme of which we believe quite naturally that it must underlie all our actions.\nAccording to this scheme, which is here applied to itself, as it were, the action begins with the mental anticipation of a future state. And this is what this anticipation looks like when fetching: I imagine the place here as it will soon be, plus myself as I am here again, and with me what I have brought with me. I think now how it will be then: in it I visualize a future present.\nBut I do not anticipate it as that which, thanks to foreign efforts, happy coincidences or divine interventions, will perhaps already become so (although I sometimes also allow myself such a thing). That it is later in such a way, as I imagine it now: I do not only imagine it daydreamingly, I do not only wish it ardently. No: I want it; I anticipate the future state of reality and of myself as my goal, as that which I have resolved to realize myself.\nBut this also means: the mental anticipation does not arbitrarily punch a future state out of the steady course of things and my life history interwoven with it. Rather, I imagine this state as the result of all the steps that connect my departure, which is about to begin, with my later return in a continuous context. The anticipation of the goal includes that of the way. I know what I want. The way together with the goal, in which it ends, is as it were compressed, condensed, folded up in thoughts already there. In this respect, anticipation is an implication. The many steps, which are destined to develop in the form of succession, are here still crowded together, gathered into one. In my plan everything planned is simultaneously present.\n Translated with www.DeepL.com/Translator (free version)"
